{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475528"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:33:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:33:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12707"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.16,0.05,0.14,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96826"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5163"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79441"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"3360"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12084"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45018"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96826"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old Indigenous boy presents to the local health care centre with a four-day history of fever, vomiting, and abdominal pain along with 24 hours of dark-coloured urine. He has no significant medical history. His immunisations are not up to date, having only received immunisations at birth. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and is clinically jaundiced with palpable hepatomegaly. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine aminotransferase (ALT) 2500 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAspartate aminotransferase (AST) 2100 U/L (5-35)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal bilirubin 25 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) 400 U/L (5-55)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase (ALP) 350 U/L (40-150)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine 53 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EINR 1.3 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAnti-HAV IgM positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral ribavirin","Oral entecavir","Intravenous corticosteroids","Intravenous immunoglobulin","Supportive care"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic symptoms and laboratory findings of acute hepatitis A infection. The diagnosis is confirmed by the positive anti-HAV IgM, which is a specific marker of acute hepatitis A infection. The most appropriate management for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Esupportive care\u003C/strong\u003E. This includes rest, maintaining hydration, and ensuring adequate nutrition. The majority of patients with hepatitis A recover spontaneously without specific antiviral treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ribavirin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiviral drug effective against some viral infections, but not hepatitis A. It is not recommended for use in children due to potential side effects, including anaemia and respiratory complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral entecavir\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for hepatitis A infection. It is a nucleoside analogue that inhibits reverse transcriptase in hepatitis B virus replication and has no activity against the hepatitis A virus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended for acute hepatitis A infection. While they have anti-inflammatory properties, they can suppress the immune system, potentially worsening the outcome of viral infections. There is no evidence supporting their use in acute hepatitis A infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E contains antibodies against the hepatitis A virus and can reduce the severity of infection in children. However, it is typically reserved for patients with fulminant or severe hepatitis A infection. In this case, while the patient is unwell, he does not appear to have severe or fulminant hepatitis requiring IVIG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while supportive care is the mainstay of treatment, close monitoring is crucial. The patient\u0027s INR is mildly elevated at 1.3, which may suggest early coagulopathy. This should be closely monitored for progression, as it could indicate a risk of acute liver failure, although this is rare in hepatitis A infections. The patient\u0027s immunisation status should also be reviewed once he has recovered from the acute illness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symptomatic care is the treatment of choice for patients with acute viral hepatitis A infection.","Hepatitis A is diagnosed by the detection of anti-HAV IgM antibodies.","Close monitoring of INR is important in hepatitis A infections due to the risk of coagulopathy."],"references":["Iorio N, John S. Hepatitis A. [Updated 2022 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459290/","Matheny SC, Kingery JE. Hepatitis A. Am Fam Physician. 2012 Dec 1;86(11):1027-34; quiz 1010-2. PMID: 23198670."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79441"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79441"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:49:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:49:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5163"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96826"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"de